title: habtools: Complexity Metrics for 3D Meshes author: Guan-Yan Chen date: 2025-05-05 output: html_document

/ Introduction

habtools (3D mesh) This tutorial demonstrates how to compute complexity metrics for 3D meshes using the habtools package.

/ Setup and Data Loading

mcap English Explanation: Load the required packages and the example mesh data mcap.

#  / Load packages
library(habtools)
## Warning: package 'habtools' was built under R version 4.3.3
library(rgl)
options(rgl.printRglwidget = TRUE)

#  / Load example mesh data
# `mcap`  habtools 
data("mcap", package = "habtools")

/ Checking your mesh

z Before calculating any metrics, visualize the mesh and ensure the z orientation is correct.

#  / Visualize the 3D mesh
plot3d(mcap)

/ Resolution Distribution

English Explanation: Compute distances between adjacent vertices in the mesh and plot a histogram to inspect variation in resolution.

#  / Calculate vector of resolutions
resvec <- Rvcg::vcgMeshres(mcap)[[2]]

#  / Plot histogram of resolutions
hist(resvec)

#  / Display summary statistics of resolutions
summary(resvec)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## 0.001307 0.005265 0.007003 0.007831 0.009410 0.043981

/ Uniform Remeshing

voxelSize English Explanation: Uniformly remesh using the minimum resolution as voxelSize to reduce variation in vertex spacing.

#  / Uniformly remesh mesh
mcap_uniform <- Rvcg::vcgUniformRemesh(
  mcap,
  silent = TRUE,
  multiSample = TRUE,
  voxelSize = min(resvec),
  mergeClost = TRUE
)

#  / Check resolution of the remeshed object
Rvcg::vcgMeshres(mcap_uniform)[[1]]  
## [1] 0.001328214
summary(Rvcg::vcgMeshres(mcap_uniform)[[2]])
##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max. 
## 0.0003464 0.0010450 0.0013561 0.0013282 0.0016327 0.0026663

R, D, H / Complexity metrics: R, D, and H

/ Fractal Dimension

cubes mesh English Explanation: Compute the fractal dimension of the mesh using the cubes method.

#  / Calculate fractal dimension
fd_result <- fd(
  mcap_uniform,
  method = "cubes",
  plot = TRUE,
  diagnose = TRUE
)
## lvec is set to c(0.003, 0.006, 0.012, 0.024, 0.048, 0.096, 0.193, 0.386).

#  D  / Extract fractal dimension
fd_result$D
## [1] 2.133279

Rugosity / Rugosity and Height Range

# Rugosity  / Compute rugosity
rg(mcap_uniform)
## L0 is set to mesh resolution (0.00132821395068341)
## [1] 3.148722
#  / Compute height range
hr(mcap_uniform)
## [1] 0.2204218

/ Planar and Surface Area

#  / Planar surface area
planar(mcap)
## L0 is set to mesh resolution (0.00783124724167033)
## [1] 0.08303158
#  / Total surface area
surface_area(mcap)
## [1] 0.2698101

/ Shape Metrics

English Explanation: Compute various metrics that describe the shape of the object.

convexity(mcap)    #  / Convexity
## [1] 0.4484716
packing(mcap)      #  / Packing
## [1] 0.8642852
sphericity(mcap)   #  / Sphericity
## [1] 0.6056971
sma(mcap)          #  / Second moment of area
## [1] 0.03294466
smv(mcap)          #  / Second moment of volume
## [1] 0.0005450781
csf(mcap)          #  / Mechanical shape factor
## z_min set to -3.74007153511047
## resolution set to 0.00783124724167033
## [1] 1816.815

DEM 2D / Transform mesh into a DEM or 2D shape

#  / Convert mesh to DEM
dem <- mesh_to_dem(mcap_uniform, res = 0.002, fill = FALSE)
#  DEM / Plot DEM
raster::plot(dem)

#  DEM  Rugosity (area ) / Compute rugosity on DEM
rg(dem, method = "area")
## data contains 13391 NA values. Results may be biased.
## L0 is set to the resolution of the raster: 0.002.
## [1] 2.767167
#  2D  / Convert mesh to 2D points
pts <- mesh_to_2d(mcap_uniform)
plot(pts, asp = 1)

#  / Compute perimeter
perimeter(pts)
## [1] 1.705922
#  / Compute circularity
circularity(pts)
## [1] 0.6123799
# 2D  (boxes ) / Compute fractal dimension in 2D
fd(pts, method = "boxes", keep_data = FALSE, plot = TRUE)

## [1] 1.263879
